{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476268"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13711"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13711"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.08,0.41,0.13,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6330"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32396"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"2388"},{"type":"tags","id":"3485"},{"type":"tags","id":"3502"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16327"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a history of recurrent bacterial infections, including otitis media and pneumonia over the past year. He has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits: pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Laboratory investigations reveal markedly low levels of all immunoglobulin classes: IgG \u0026lt;2 g/L (3.0-16.0), IgA \u0026lt;0.1 g/L (0.2-1.0), IgM \u0026lt;0.2 g/L (0.2-2.0). Flow cytometry shows an absence of B cells in peripheral blood.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains the underlying pathophysiology of this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deficiency of CD40 ligand","Deficiency of adenosine deaminase","Deficiency of Bruton tyrosine kinase","Deficiency of complement component C3","Deficiency of interleukin-2 receptor"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with X-linked agammaglobulinaemia (XLA), a condition characterised by recurrent bacterial infections and low levels of all immunoglobulin classes. The underlying pathophysiology involves a \u003Cstrong\u003Edeficiency of Bruton tyrosine kinase\u003C/strong\u003E, which is crucial for B cell development and function. Without this enzyme, B cells cannot mature, leading to a profound lack of circulating immunoglobulins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficiency of adenosine deaminase\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), which affects both B and T cells, not just B cells as seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficiency of CD40 ligand\u003C/strong\u003E leads to hyper-IgM syndrome, characterised by normal or elevated levels of IgM but low levels of other immunoglobulin classes, which does not match this patient\u0027s immunoglobulin profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficiency of complement component C3\u003C/strong\u003E results in increased susceptibility to certain bacterial infections but does not specifically affect B cell development or immunoglobulin production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeficiency of interleukin-2 receptor\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with X-linked severe combined immunodeficiency, primarily affecting T cell function rather than B cells and antibody production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bruton tyrosine kinase is essential for B cell development and function, and its deficiency leads to X-linked agammaglobulinaemia."],"references":["Mazhar M, Waseem M. Agammaglobulinemia. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK555941/","El-Sayed ZA, Abramova I, Aldave JC, Al-Herz W, Bezrodnik L, Boukari R, et al. X-linked agammaglobulinemia (XLA):Phenotype, diagnosis, and therapeutic challenges around the world. World Allergy Organ J. 2019 Mar 22;12(3):100018. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6439403/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32396"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32396"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-26T20:18:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-01T20:04:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6330"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47669"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"descrip